2. How Avro works (Step-by-step)

We create an Avro schema file (.avsc) defining the fields
Using Avro plugin, Java classes are generated at build time
We use those generated classes to create event objects
Kafka producer serializes the object into binary format
Consumer deserializes using the same schema
{
  "type": "record",
  "name": "HoldEvent",
  "namespace": "com.example",
  "fields": [
    {"name": "accountId", "type": "string"},
    {"name": "amount", "type": "double"},
    {"name": "status", "type": "string"}
  ]
}
spring:
  kafka:
    producer:
      key-serializer: org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringSerializer
      value-serializer: io.confluent.kafka.serializers.KafkaAvroSerializer
We configure serializer in YAML so that KafkaTemplate knows how to convert Java objects into a format that can be sent over Kafka.
Since we use Avro, we use KafkaAvroSerializer to convert objects into binary format.

memory leaks how to overcome..?
Kafka itself does not usually cause memory leaks, but memory issues can arise due to improper producer or consumer configurations. For example, large message sizes, high batching, or slow consumers can lead to memory pressure.
We can overcome this by tuning producer configurations like batch size and buffer memory, ensuring efficient consumer processing, and monitoring system performance.
In our project, we use Avro for lightweight messages and Cassandra for persistence to avoid memory-related issues

--------Springboot--------------
Spring Boot is built on top of the Spring Framework and simplifies application development by providing default configurations. It follows an opinionated approach to reduce boilerplate code.
The application starts with @SpringBootApplication, which is a combination of @Configuration, @EnableAutoConfiguration, and @ComponentScan.
@Configuration is used to define beans, @EnableAutoConfiguration automatically configures beans based on classpath dependencies, and @ComponentScan scans the package and registers components as beans.
It also provides embedded servers like Tomcat, so applications can run independently without external deployment.

----dispatcher servlet---------
Client sends HTTP request
Request first goes to DispatcherServlet
DispatcherServlet consults HandlerMapping to find the correct controller
It calls the respective controller method
Controller processes request and returns response
DispatcherServlet sends response back to client

--------dependency injection--------------
Dependency Injection is a design pattern where Spring manages object creation and injects dependencies, reducing tight coupling.
@Autowired is used to automatically inject dependencies by type from the Spring container.
Internally, when the application starts, Spring creates the ApplicationContext, scans for components, creates beans, and injects dependencies wherever @Autowired is used.
If multiple beans of the same type exist, we use @Qualifier to specify which one to inject.

@Controller returns view names by default, whereas @ResponseBody converts return values into HTTP response body. @RestController is a combination of both and is used for REST APIs.
